") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://www.buddymedia.com/newsroom/2012/10/michael-kass-lazerow-named-leaders-of-the-future/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0"))) ("How Your Brand Can Embrace Social Good" "<div id=\"attachment_18805\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\" style=\"width: 600px\"><a href=\"/newsroom/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Social-Good.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-18805\" title=\"Social Good\" src=\"/newsroom/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Social-Good.jpg\" alt=\" \" width=\"590\" height=\"443\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Credit: http://www.flickr.com/photos/howardlake/4141454994/</p></div><p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">Social media has the power to make the world a better place. Last week, NYC was home to the <a href=\"http://mashable.com/sgs/\" target=\"_blank\">Social Good Summit</a>, where this topic was the star. But you didn’t have to be on Manhattan’s Upper East Side to join the conversation or learn how to do some social good of your own.</p><p>CEOs, Nobel Prize winners, government officials, celebrities and the public from all over the world shared their stories, ideas and insights on social good across social media during the summit, bringing in <strong>98,617</strong> conversations. What does this mean? Yes, social good is a good thing. But moreover, organizations across the world are realizing the opportunity and embracing it.</p><p>How can your organization embrace social good? Consider these ideas.</p><h2>Apply your Data</h2><p>One of the most retweeted quotes at the conference was from <a href=\"https://twitter.com/todd_Park\">Todd Park</a>, Chief Technology Officer at the White House:</p><p>“It’s about turning government into a platform for open innovation. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Data by itself is useless</span>. I can’t feed my baby daughter data, as much as I’d love to because I love data. <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">It’s only useful if you apply it to create an actual public benefit.</span> You need appliers — you need entrepreneurs to know data’s available in order for them to turn it into awesomeness.”</p><p>Social media provides us with a slew of data. Dissect it to pull out the insights that will benefit your community. For instance, through social media monitoring, you may uncover cries for help in your community. It could even be as simple as a <a href=\"http://www.buddymedia.com/newsroom/2012/09/how-a-facebook-ad-helped-find-a-missing-cat/\">missing cat</a> or larger issues around poverty. Uncover these stories and find ways to get involved.</p><h2>Involve your Community</h2><p>During the conference, the White House Council on Women and Girls launched the <a href=\"http://equalfutures.challenge.gov/\">Equal Futures Partnership</a>, where individuals can enter a contest to create apps that help promote civic education and inspire girls to serve as leaders. Consider how social media and technology can serve as a means for the public to get involved in your efforts.</p><h2>Reach Out to Leaders</h2><p>There are influential voices in your community that may come in the form of bloggers or super Twitter users. They have opinions, ideas and a following. By connecting and developing relationships with these social media leaders, you can further spread your message and have a supportive voice in the community.</p><p>As Jimmy Wales, founder of Wikipedia, shared at the summit, “The Internet is allowing for us to really experience people in some of the most distant places in the world — as other people just like us. So get to know people, seek out bloggers from a country you’re kind of curious about. It’s about building empathy and breaking through to the point of recognizing people as people.”</p><p><em>What opportunities for social good are apparent in your community? How can your organization make the world a better place with social media? Read more about the <a href=\"http://mashable.com/sgs/\" target=\"_blank\">Social Good Summit here</a>.</em></p>" "http://www.buddymedia.com/newsroom/2012/10/how-your-brand-can-embrace-social-good/" (20588 17450) new 4 nil nil ((title nil "How Your Brand Can Embrace Social Good") (link nil "http://www.buddymedia.com/newsroom/2012/10/how-your-brand-can-embrace-social-good/") (comments nil "http://www.buddymedia.com/newsroom/2012/10/how-your-brand-can-embrace-social-good/#comments") (pubDate nil "Wed, 03 Oct 2012 13:56:58 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Amanda Nelson") (category nil "Blog") (category nil "jimmy wales") (category nil "social good") (category nil "social good summit") (category nil "social media") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://www.buddymedia.com/newsroom/?p=18795") (description nil "Social media has the power to make the world a better place. Last week, NYC was home to the Social Good Summit, where this topic was the star. But you didn’t have to be on Manhattan’s Upper East Side to join the conversation or learn how to do some social good of your own. CEOs, [...]") (content:encoded nil "<div id=\"attachment_18805\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\" style=\"width: 600px\"><a href=\"/newsroom/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Social-Good.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-18805\" title=\"Social Good\" src=\"/newsroom/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Social-Good.jpg\" alt=\" \" width=\"590\" height=\"443\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">Credit: http://www.flickr.com/photos/howardlake/4141454994/</p></div><p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">Social media has the power to make the world a better place. Last week, NYC was home to the <a href=\"http://mashable.com/sgs/\" target=\"_blank\">Social Good Summit</a>, where this topic was the star. But you didn’t have to be on Manhattan’s Upper East Side to join the conversation or learn how to do some social good of your own.</p><p>CEOs, Nobel Prize winners, government officials, celebrities and the public from all over the world shared their stories, ideas and insights on social good across social media during the